data.name: fill_sinks_before_checkbox.ToolTip
data.value:
Removes sinks from the input DEM.
Sinks are often seen as input DEM errors. Unless removed, sinks in LORICA are treated as valid landscape elements, i.e. they are searched for an outlet, hydrologically functional and deposition into them occurs according to a special set of rules.
Reference: Temme et al, 1996. Computers and Geosciences 32(4): 452-461

data.name: label5.ToolTip
data.value:
Input filenames are not available when both f(x,y) and f(t) are unchecked. In that case, only single values are input LORICA will use filename in the following way:
1. When f(x,y) is checked but f(t) is not checked, filename is the ascii grid that will be read. Example: filename = use.asc ; LORICA will read use.asc
2. When f(x,y) and f(t) are checked, filename is the prefix for a series of ascii grid files with the timestep following the prefix. Example: filename = use.asc ; LORICA will read use1.asc, use2.asc, use3.asc etc
3. When f(x,y) is not checked, but f(t) is checked, filename is the text file containing (spatially uniform) timeseries. The number of values in this file should at least equal the number of timesteps in the run. LORICA will start using the first value. Example: rainfall.asc can look like: 0.67 0.54 0.87 0.70 etc

data.name: groupBox9.ToolTip
data.value:
The process description for biological (and other) weathering uses the humped model and is based on Minasny and McBratney (2006, Geoderma 133).
Parameters :
P0 (m t-1) = maximum weathering rate of bedrock k1 (t-1) = weathering rate constant when soil thickness > hc k2 (t-1) = weathering rate constant when soil thickness <= hc Pa = weathering rate at steady state
hc, the soil thickness where maximum weathering occurs is
hc = (ln(k2/k1)) / (k2-k1)
